    "The histogram of the resulting distribution of the number of microminima is shown in Fig. 9.",
    "Finally, by extending arguments found in Wambsganss (1992), Granot et al. (2003), it can be shown that the average magnification of a single micro-minimum is:",
    "where μ macro / n is the macro-magnification from Eq.",
    "(14) divided by the expected number of micro-minima, and P is the probability that location x mm is a minimum and not a saddlepoint.",
    "A very useful tool for microlensing studies is the magnification field on the source plane induced by an ensemble of microlenses."
